  "language": "en",
  "text": "By the end of this section, you'll understand how sanitation fits into your HACCP system, what auditors specifically look for, and why your paperwork must match what actually happens on the floor. In most bakeries, sanitation is a prerequisite program under your HACCP plan. This defines how it's managed, verified, and audited. Your HACCP plan identifies hazards, establishes critical control points, and sets monitoring procedures. It assumes certain foundational conditions are in place, clean equipment, controlled environments, trained personnel. These foundations are your prerequisite programs, and sanitation is one of the most important. When sanitation fails, HACCP assumptions become invalid. Here's a concrete example. Your HACCP plan identifies the oven as a CCP for biological hazards. The bake step kills salmonella and listeria, but your plan assumes the product then enters a clean, controlled, post-bake environment. If your cooling area has a listeria problem because your sanitation program isn't controlling biofilms in the spiral cooler, the oven CCP still works, but the HACCP system has been undermined. You baked the pathogen out and then reintroduced it through a failed prerequisite. That's not a corrective action note. That's a system-level failure. What do auditors actually look for? Let me walk through the key expectations from BRC and FSSC 22,000. SSOPs, a documented procedure for every cleaning task, each one specifying scope, chemicals at what concentration, method step-by-step, safety precautions, and verification criteria. SSOPs must be current, reflecting the equipment you have today, not what you had when the procedure was written. Master sanitation schedule, auditors check completeness, risk-based frequency, assigned responsibility, and evidence of completion. They'll cross-reference against the floor. If your schedule says overheads are cleaned monthly, the auditor may check the last three months of records and then look up at the cable trays. Chemical records. Every cleaning chemical should have a documented approval, accessible SDS, specified dilution rates verified through titration and secure storage segregated from ingredients. Verification data. ATP results, environmental monitoring results, microbiological tests, and pre-op records. Auditors want trends, not just individual results. A folder of ATP results with no analysis is data collection, not verification. Training records. Documented training for every team member on their SSOPs, chemical safety, allergen awareness, and bakery-specific hazards. Periodic, not just induction. CAPPA. Corrective and preventive action for every deviation, failure, or non-conformance. What went wrong? What you did to contain it. The root cause investigation. What you changed to prevent recurrence. Evidence the change was effective. Here's what separates a pass from a high score. Your paperwork must match the floor. If your SSOP says you disassemble and inspect a depositor nozzle daily, the auditor will check the equipment. If there's dried dough in the nozzle bore, your procedure is either not followed or not effective. Either way, non-conformance. Auditors look for disconnects. Clean records with dirty equipment. Detailed SSOPs with untrained operators. ATP results showing no failures ever, which is statistically improbable and suggests managed results. Recap. Sanitation is a prerequisite program underpinning HACCP. When it fails, HACCP assumptions become invalid. Auditors expect SSOPs, risk-based schedules, chemical records, verification trends, training records, and CAPA. The critical standard, paperwork must match floor reality."
